The DRAFT! What happens when they reactivate the DRAFT? They were probably ready to reactivate the DRAFT when Ronny Ray-gun and his buddies were getting into El Salvador.<br><br>
I was drafted in 1966, but I wasn't sent to Vietnam, thankfully. And I sure didn't volunteer to fight against some enemy that was a complete mystery to me what threat they posed.<br><br>
There was a National Gaurd member in my basic training platoon from Baltimore who had been called to active duty.<br>
He was not in very good physical condition. When he developed a really bad blister that  became raw meat on one foot, they just kept running him in training. They had their usual way of discouraging trainees from going on sick call, GI's will relate to that. Finally it became infected to the point where one night he went to the CQ because of high fever and being almost delerious. The CQ got him to the hospital at FT. Jackson (drag-ass Hill, I loved that hill!) where he sat in the waiting room until he became completly delerious and ran outside wandering around and collapsed in some bushes, where they found him later --DEAD.<br><br>
There's no mention of the GI's who died in training for the War on the wall, is there? His name belongs on that wall in DC, doesn't it?<br><br>
I can't even remember his name. I can't even remember my basic- training company's designation.<br><br>
I too spent some time at that hospital at Ft. Jackson, I came down with pnenomia, where you had to buff the floor of the ward if your fever was less than 100 deg.-cool, huh?
